at=.webp","email":"xieda@bytedance.com","name":"xieda"},{"avatar":"https://s1-fs.pstatp.com/static-resource/v1/f27851c0-d3e8-4851-a606-1a3d9361b82g~?image_size=72x72&cut_type=&quality=&format=png&sticker_format=.webp","email":"xieweicheng@bytedance.com","name":"xieweicheng"},{"avatar":"https://s3-fs.pstatp.com/static-resource/v1/43d80005ffccbded38e9~?image_size=72x72&cut_type=&quality=&format=png&sticker_format=.webp","email":"yeyuanfeng@bytedance.com","name":"yeyuanfeng"}],"repository":{"type":"git","url":"https://code.byted.org/nodejs/byted-service"}},"1.12.10":{"_npmVersion":"lerna/undefined/node@v14.18.1+x64 (linux)","dependencies":{"@byted-service/env":"^1.11.0","@byted-service/logger":"^2.0.9","fast-deep-equal":"^3.1.3","tslib":"^1.9.3"},"readme":"# @byted-service/consul 服务发现\n\n[![bnpm](https://web-bnpm.byted.org/badge/v/@byted-service/consul.svg?style=flat-square)](https://web-bnpm.byted.org/package/@byted-service/consul) [![download](https://2y8ngapf.fn.bytedance.net/d?p=@byted-service/consul)](https://web-bnpm.byted.org/package/@byted-service/consul)\n\n[简体中文](https://code.byted.org/nodejs/byted-service/blob/master/packages/consul/README.md) | [English](https://code.byted.org/nodejs/byted-service/blob/master/packages/consul/README.en.md) | [CHANGELOG](https://code.byted.org/nodejs/byted-service/blob/master/packages/consul/CHANGELOG.md)\n\n## Installation\n\n```bash\nnpm install @byted-service/consul --registry=http://bnpm.byted.org\n```\n\n## Service address query\n\n### 1. Create Consul instance\n\n```javascript\nconst Consul = require('@byted-service/consul');\n\nconst options = {\n    host: '127.0.0.1',\n    port: 2280,\n    cache: new Map(),\n    cacheTimeoutMS: 15 * 1000,\n};\nconst consul = new Consul(options);\n```\n\n`options`\n\n**NOTE: Many libs that depend on @byted-service/consul might set the `options` with different default value.** Some libs need to obey the traffic scheduling strategy based on env. e.g. @byted-service/rpc and @byted-service/fetch, so that these libs would set env as `prod`, set cluster as `default` and set enableTrafficScheduling as `true`.\n\n-   `host`: Consul Agent address, default is [`env.gatewayByEnv`](https://tosv.byted.org/obj/typedoc/byted-service/env/index.html#gatewaybyenv), as tested locally Fillable development machine address, which can be overridden by CONSUL_HTTP_HOST and ROUTE_IP, where CONSUL_HTTP_HOST has higher priority than ROUTE_IP (in line with other languages)\n-   `port`: Consul Agent port, default is 2280, can be overridden by CONSUL_HTTP_PORT\n-   `cache`: Cache interface. You need to implement three interfaces:`get`, `set`, and`keys`. The default is Map instance.\n-   `cacheTimeoutMS`: cache expiration time, in milliseconds, default is 15 \\* 1000\n-   `forceHttp`: Force to use host:port(not unix domain socket),default is false\n-   `logger`: Logger instance\n\n### 2. Query service address based on service PSM\n\n```javascript\n// Get all query results\nconst lookupAddresses = await consul.lookup('toutiao.tos.tosapi', {\n    env: 'prod',\n    cluster: 'default',\n});\nconsole.log('lookup:', lookupAddresses);\n\n// Get the first query result\nconst firstAddress = await consul.first('toutiao.tos.tosapi', {\n    env: 'prod',\n    cluster: 'default',\n});\nconsole.log('first address:', firstAddress);\n\n// Get a query result randomly\nconst randomAddress = await consul.random('toutiao.tos.tosapi', {\n    env: 'prod',\n    cluster: 'default',\n});\nconsole.log('random address:', randomAddress);\n```\n\nWhen querying, you can specify query options `options', and the query method will filter the query results according to the query options.`options` supports the following values:\n\n-   `env(string)`: environment variable, default is `*`, if you want to get an instance of `prod`, set it to`prod`;\n-   `cluster(string)`: The cluster name. The default is `*`. If you want to get the address of `default`, set it to`default`.\n-   `enableTrafficScheduling(boolean)`: Allow traffic scheduling policy to be enabled. The operation of filtering addresses after opening will follow the following process. For details, please refer to [Env-based Traffic Scheduling #Standard Implementation](https://bytedance.feishu.cn/space/doc/ws0Kg2Q539Rzqc18VFc98f # 2kHzIi):\n\n    1. Selecting downstream based on Env is after filtering downstream processes based on Cluster and before selecting downstream processes based on Weight.\n    2. If the Env in the request is not the default Env, return a list of instances where the Env in the downstream instance is equal to the Env in the request.\n    3. If the list of b procedures is empty, the list of instances where Env is equal to the default Env from the downstream instance is returned.\n    4. If the Env in the request is the default Env, then the Env in the downstream instance is the union of the default Env and the small flow Env.\n\n-   `withAddrFamily (string)`: IPV6 addressing, not transmitted by default, and only return IPv4 address (If you need to support `IPv6`, it is recommended to set`withAddrFamily: auto` in no special scenarios)\n\n    -   When setting `withAddrFamily: v6`, only IPv6 address is returned (empty if there is no IPv6)\n    -   When setting `withAddrFamily: v4`, only return IPv4 address\n    -   When setting `withAddrFamily: dual-stack`, all IPv6 and IPv4 addresses will be returned (if a machine is bound to dual stack addresses, both IPv4 and IPv6 addresses will be returned) - When setting `withAddrFamily: auto`, the currently supported IP version will be automatically judged according to the environment variables (for example, if only IPv4 is supported, then only the IPv4 address is returned. When dual stack is supported, [the IPv6 address will be returned first](https://code.byted.org/nodejs/byted-service/issues/532#note_14926600))\n\n    > When using IPv6 addressing, you may need to pay attention to the following issues\n\n    ```javascript\n    import net from 'net';\n\n    // Some modules require the following conversion when using IPV6 to establish a connection, for example: http://[fdbd: dc02: ff: 1: 1: 225: 126: 11]: 2280/v1/xxx\n    if (net.isIPv6(host)) {\n        host = `[${host}]`;\n    }\n    ```\n\n    alternative you can also directy use compatible `address.uri` to send request\n\n    ```js\n    const address = await consul.lookup('p.s.m');\n    await request(`http://${address.uri}/v1/xxx`);\n    ```\n\n## Service address change monitoring\n\nA `ServiceWatcher` class is mounted under the`Consul` module, through which you can listen for changes in the service address. The `ServiceWatcher` class polls the Consul Agent periodically, and compares the obtained result with the previous result. If the address list changes, the caller is notified through an event.\n\n```javascript\nconst { Logger } = require('@byted-service/logger');\nconst Consul = require('@byted-service/consul');\nconst { ServiceWatcher } = Consul;\n\n// Create a ServiceWatcher instance to listen for service address changes (the watcher method supports chained calls)\nconst watcher = new ServiceWatcher({\n    interval: 5000, // polling interval, unit ms, default 5000\n    consul: {\n        // Consul configuration options\n        host: '10 .3.23.42 ',\n        port: 2280,\n        logger: new Logger(),\n    },\n    unref: false, // Keep the event loop of the parent process running\n});\n\n// Add Service\nwatcher.addService('toutiao.tos.tosapi', { env: 'prod', cluster: 'default' });\nwatcher.addService('toutiao.redis.ies_fe_gecko', {\n    env: 'prod',\n    cluster: 'default',\n});\n\n// start listening\nwatcher.watch();\n\n// Register address change event callback\nwatcher.on('update', (service, addresses) => {\n    console.log(service, addresses);\n});\n```\n\n## Cache and Updater\n\n### Cache\n\nWe now support consul's caching capabilities.\n\n#### Buffer\n\nThe buffer is an object with a standard API.The following methods need to be implemented for use by consul.\n\n```js\n// return cached result\ncache.get('key');\n\n// set cache\ncache.set('key', [...]);\n```\n\nThe cache strategy here can be managed by itself, such as providing the simplest Map () object as a cache. You can also use lru-cache. As long as it supports the get/set method.\n\nConsul will preferentially use the data in the cache before initiating a parse query\nIf the cached data exists, the cached result will be returned directly; if the cache does not exist, the request will be actually parsed; after the parsing is successful, Consul will write the result to the cache.\n\nWe can provide a global cache, or we can assign a special cache to a Consul instance:\n\n```js\n// Set global cache\nConsul.setCache(myCache);\n\n// use global cache\nnew Consul();\n\n// single instance uses cache\nnew Consul({ cache: myCache });\n\n// Set the cache of the instance directly\nnew Consul().setCache(myCache);\n```\n\n> By default, we do not provide global buffers; this is consistent with previous versions.\n\n#### data format in consul buffer\n\nThe data in the buffer is psm as the key value.Example:\n\n```js\n{\n    \"some.psm.a\": {\n        \"addresses\": [\n            {\n                \"host\": \"1.1.1.1\",\n                \"port\": 1111,\n                \"tags\": {\n                    \"env\": \"prod\",\n                    \"cluster\": \"default\"\n                }\n            },\n            ...\n        ],\n        \"updatedAt\": 1565067698350,\n        \"hash\": \"e289fbacf9818220eabb7dcd687ae1e7\",\n    },\n    \"some.psm.b\": {\n        \"addresses\": [\n            {\n                \"host\": \"2.2.2.2\",\n                \"port\": 2222,\n                \"tags\": {\n                    \"env\": \"prod\",\n                    \"cluster\": \"default\"\n                }\n            },\n            ...\n        ],\n        \"updatedAt\": 1565067698350,\n        \"hash\": \"e289fbacf9818220eabb7dcd687ae1e7\",\n    }\n}\n```\n\n> If you want to manage the contents of the buffer manually, please follow this format.\n\n#### Force update cache\n\nIn some cases, you may need to force a cache update.\nWe added a `force` parameter to `lookup` /`first` / `random` of consul to force a query.\nThat is, you can do:\n\n```js\nconsul.lookup(psm, { env: 'prod', cluster: 'default' }, true);\nconsul.first(psm, { env: 'prod', cluster: 'default' }, true);\nconsul.random(psm, { env: 'prod', cluster: 'default' }, true);\n```\n\n> Force update will write result to cache\n\n### Updater\n\nThe service corresponding to consul may change. Therefore, the parsing result cannot be cached forever, and an update strategy is required.\nGenerally speaking, there are two popular strategies for cached updates: 1 expired passive elimination 2 regular active updates.\nThe cache miss during passive elimination may cause the instantaneous parsing to trigger the real query. Therefore, there will be an avalanche phenomenon, which will cause the system performance to decline.\nTherefore, we recommend implementing an Updater to observe the cache and perform regular (5 seconds) active updates.\n\nWe provide a simple `Updater`, you can use it like this:\n\n```js\nconst { Updater } = require('@byted-service/consul');\n\n// Simple illustration here, using a Map object to act as a buffer\nconst cache = new Map();\n\n// You can set the update frequency, the default is 5000ms\nconst updater = new Updater({ interval: 5000 });\n\n// listen buffer\nupdater.watch(cache);\n\n// If necessary, you can stop listening\nupdater.unwatch();\n```\n\nThis simple `Updater` runs every 5000ms. It will parse all key values in the cache, which is psm, and write the results to the cache.\n\nIn addition to the need for the buffer to provide get/set methods, it also needs to support the keys method to get all the psm. Specifically, the keys method returns an iterator or array.\n\n#### Custom implementation of Updater\n\nThe logic of the Updater can be completely customized to meet special needs. The self-implementation only needs to match the buffer.\n\n### Recommended usage\n\nWe recommend using a simple cache with a simple updater. Example:\n\n```js\n// First perform simple settings\nconst Consul = require('@byted-service/consul');\nconst cache = new Map();\nconst updater = new Consul.Updater();\nupdater.watch(cache);\nConsul.setCache(cache);\n\n// Now you can use Consul\nnew Consul(). lookup(). then (...);\n```\n\n### processing consul request timeout that caused by ROUTE_IP or GATEWAY.\n\nWhen developing locally, sometimes using consul will time out and see the following errors:\n\n```bash\nRequestError: Error: connect ETIMEOUT 10.17.91.134:2280\n```\n\nThis is because consul use the address `10.17.91.134:2280` to lookup service. If the address `10.17.91.134` has expired or network is isolated，the above error message may appear. **At this time , it is recommended to set env variable ROUTE_IP that point your own devbox address**, e.g. if your devbox IP is\n10.227.30.24:\n\n```\nROUTE_IP=10.227.30.24 node index.js\n```\n\n#### how to get BOE envirenment IP address\n\n-   use devbox development machine ip(you need to execute sudo /opt/tiger/consul_devbox/bin/switch.sh boe in the development machine to switch consul to BOE)\n-   use TCE BOE instance IP\n-   use the public development machine IP: 10.225.130.44\n\n#### how to obtain the online environment IP address\n\n-   use devbox development machine ip(you need to execute sudo /opt/tiger/consul_devbox/bin/switch.sh langfang in the development machine to switch consul to lf)\n-   use the online TCE instance IP\n\nSee also the document about devbox's consul service switch: https://bytedance.feishu.cn/docs/O3voSqlVef22bDoeh97BKd#EdTb1X\n\n## FAQ\n\n### specify options.host、options.port , but does not work\n\nBy default, `@byted-service/consul` will first detect whether there is `/opt/tmp/sock/consul.sock` in the environment, and use it directly if it exists (exist in TCE, devbox)\n\nThe priority of